{"id":14881824,"mediaExerciseId":"a2e0e651-892f-4c02-a9a6-35c509b77ac8","exerciseName":"8","chapterName":"23","chapterTitle":"Enterprise Risk Management","groupId":612487,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":786,"solutions":[{"id":6004741,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we will talk about possible hedging strategies that a company can use to address the expected risks they might run into in the future","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"A put option and a call option are two opposite things. In a put option, the buyer of the contract has the right, but not the obligation, to sell the product. On the other hand, a call option gives the buyer of the contract the right, but not the obligation, to buy the product.\n\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/7478688edf23c683b95919a7e328e07e/596001148d635fe38c288622a1c2d9c9/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/7478688edf23c683b95919a7e328e07e/596001148d635fe38c288622a1c2d9c9/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The company can then place a put option on their bonds and a call option on their interest rates. This means that if the price of the bond decreases, and/or the interest rate increases, they will still gain some profit which can offset whatever loss they may sustain in the future.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":141,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/22/01/11/7478688edf23c683b95919a7e328e07e/3b33f494d2beec47a8eb019e050cce29/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.n